          Proposed rule <br><br>
          Dear Mr. Christian, <br><br>
          I have reviewed the Federal Register 57(13): 2236-2238 concerning the above <br><br>
          Proposed Rule for the Agent Orange claims of Vietnam Veterans. I have the <br><br>
          following comments: <br><br>
          It is my understanding that the major use of Agent Orange phenoxy <br><br>
          herbicides 2,4-dichlorophenoxy acetic acid (2,4-D) and 2,4,5- <br><br>
          trichlorophenoxy acetic acid (2,4,5-T) occurred between 1965 and 1970, with <br><br>
          exposure to troops occurring until approximately 1973. <br><br>
          On a medical basis, I believe that the rules proposed by the Department of <br><br>
          Veterans Affairs are faulty and based upon unscientific ideas for the <br><br>
          following reasons: <br><br>
          1. While peripheral neuropathy frequently manifests itself within a <br><br>
          short time after exposure to a neurotoxic agent, there are frequent <br><br>
          problems with diagnosis because of <br><br>
          a) failure to correctly diagnosis a neuropathy, especially with subtle <br><br>
          neuropathic changes, and <br><br>
          b) failure to correctly diagnosis a neuropathy by physicians who are <br><br>
          unfamiliar with the problem, and <br><br>
          c) failure of a Veteran to present him/herself for evaluation of <br><br>
          neurotoxic problems because of lack of medical care, and/or lack of <br><br>
          appreciation of the serious symptoms that he/she may have experienced. <br><br>
          2. Connected to #1 is the problem of subsequent exposure to neurotoxic <br><br>
          agents. Would a Veteran be denied compensation if <br><br>
          --------------------------------------------------------------------------- <br><br>
          he/she worked as a pest control operator or in agriculture where the very <br><br>
          same chemicals were used? Who can say but that his/her previous exposure <br><br>
          to Agent Orange herbicides did not initiate the neuropathic changes? <br><br>
          3. Connected to #1 and #2 is the problem of subsequent exposure to <br><br>
          other neurotoxic agents such as solvents. Because a Veteran earned a <br><br>
          living in an industry that employed these chemicals (legally, I might add), <br><br>
          would his/her claim be denied, even though the initial neuropathic insult <br><br>
          occurred as a result of his/her exposure in Vietnam? <br><br>
          4. How does one assess the claim of a Veteran who was not only exposed <br><br>
          to the Agent Orange chemicals, but at the same time was exposed to other <br><br>
          neurotoxic agents (such as solvents, fuels, etc.) while serving in Vietnam? <br><br>
          5. Taking into consideration items #1, #2, #3, and #4 above, I cannot <br><br>
          understand how an age restriction can be applied. Indeed, do the records <br><br>
          show that the diagnosis of peripheral neuropathy has actually been made on <br><br>
          any Veterans? How many? And when? What do the actual records show? <br><br>
          6. I agree with no restriction as to alcoholism, because the frequent <br><br>
          sequela of combat stress is the use of alcohol in an attempt to alleviate <br><br>
          stress, no matter how successful and unfortunate. <br><br>
          7. Diabetes should NOT be an exclusion. Review of earlier studies has <br><br>
          showed an increased incidence of diabetes mellitus among Vietnam Veterans. <br><br>
          The mechanism is unclear, as to whether the Agent Orange components cause <br><br>
          direct damage to the pancreas, or by some other indirect mechanism. <br><br>
          (Certainly this is an area ripe for study, and I urge that it be undertaken <br><br>
          in animals.) <br><br>
          8. It is my understanding that it was the practice of the military to <br><br>
          distribute cigarettes to troops in the field. Since this was the official <br><br>
          policy of the military command, how can they in any conscience eliminate a <br><br>
          lung cancer claim? Should we thus conclude that all personnel smoked in <br><br>
          order to establish a :baseline&quot;? If not, how do we consider the Veteran <br><br>
          with lung cancer who did not smoke cigarettes at all? <br><br>
          9. I believe that we, the members of the American Legion Science <br><br>
          Committee, should review the approximately 40 studies, and the analysis of <br><br>
          those studies as prepared by the Veteran's Advisory Committee on <br><br>
          Environmental Hazards (VACEH) to make an independent determination, as to <br><br>
          the actual criteria used by the VACEH to deny benefits for lung cancer. <br><br>
          10. Lastly, it must be emphasized that the assessment of the toxicology <br><br>
          of the Agent Orange herbicide MUST include the herbicidal chemicals <br><br>
          themselves (2,4-D and 2,4,5-T) as well as <br><br>
          --------------------------------------------------------------------------- <br><br>
          the contaminating dioxins in setting policy. It is important to understand <br><br>
          that the phenoxy herbicides carry neurotoxic (and additional toxic effects) <br><br>
          separate from dioxin contamination. <br><br>
          Please contact me if any of this requires additional information and/or <br><br>
          clarification. <br><br>
          Sincerely yours, <br><br>
          s/ <br><br>
